<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>🎓 What You Learned — Image Metadata</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
</head>
<body>
  <div class="edu-page">
    <a href="/" class="back-link">← Back to Challenges</a>
    <img src="/images/logo.png" alt="EECS Girls Who Tech Camp" class="page-logo">

    <div class="edu-card">
      <div class="congrats">📸</div>
      <h1>Challenge 4 Complete!</h1>
      <p style="color:#9090b0; margin-top:5px;">Secrets in a Photo</p>
      <div class="flag-reveal"><%= flag %></div>
    </div>

    <div class="edu-section">
      <h2>📚 What You Just Learned</h2>
      <p>You performed your first act of <strong>digital forensics</strong> by analyzing a photo's <strong>metadata</strong> — data about data. Digital photos contain <strong>EXIF data</strong> (Exchangeable Image File Format) that records information invisible to the naked eye.</p>
      <p>EXIF metadata can include: the camera model, date and time, shutter speed, ISO, GPS coordinates where the photo was taken, software used to edit it, and even the photographer's name or comments.</p>
      <p>You used an EXIF viewer to extract this hidden information and found the flag embedded in the image's comment field.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="edu-section">
      <div class="real-world-box">
        <h3>🌍 Real-World Application</h3>
        <p>Photo metadata has played a role in many real investigations. Law enforcement uses EXIF GPS data to locate where a photo was taken. Journalists have verified the authenticity of photos by checking metadata timestamps. In one famous case, a fugitive was tracked down because the photos he posted online still contained GPS coordinates. On the flip side, this is why social media platforms strip EXIF data from uploaded photos — to protect your privacy!</p>
      </div>

      <div class="career-box">
        <h3>👩‍💻 Career Connection</h3>
        <p><strong>Digital Forensics Analysts</strong> examine electronic evidence for law enforcement, corporations, and government agencies. They recover deleted files, analyze metadata, trace digital footprints, and present evidence in court. It's like being a detective, but for the digital world! Many forensics analysts have backgrounds in computer science or cybersecurity.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="edu-section">
      <h2>🔑 Key Takeaways</h2>
      <p>1. Every digital photo carries hidden metadata (EXIF data) beyond the visible image.</p>
      <p>2. EXIF data can reveal sensitive information like GPS location, timestamps, and device info.</p>
      <p>3. Always strip metadata from photos before sharing them publicly (most social media does this automatically).</p>
      <p>4. Forensic investigators use metadata as evidence — it can reveal when, where, and how a file was created.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="next-btns">
      <a href="/" class="next-btn secondary">← All Challenges</a>
      <% if (hasNext) { %>
      <a href="/challenge/<%= nextNum %>" class="next-btn">Next Challenge →</a>
      <% } %>
    </div>
  </div>
</body>
</html>
